title: For Sale:  Remington Rand 1911 X-Series
postcontent: Original box and paperwork. Frame is 1918. Gun has a few scratches on the frame and slide, otherwise as new. "Original X-Series 1911 that came out of the Springfield Armory. X-Numbers: Three seperate sets of replacement X-numbers were assigned to pistols with missing or defaced serial numbers. The first series began in April 1924, with replacement number X1000, and continued until 1953 with terminal number X4385. At least during the first few years all pistols were renumbered at Springfield Armory except X1179 and X1180, which were assigned to the Philippine Department on December 23, 1924. A few of the early X-numbered pistols were assembled at Springfield Armory with unnumbered receivers left over after World War I, easily recognized since there is no assembler's mark or acceptance mark.

title: For Sale:  20" Saiga 7.62x39
postcontent:
I have a customized, converted Saiga 20" chambered in 7.62x39 for sale.  It has the following:  - Threaded muzzle with 74 style brake - Installed bullet guide so that all magazines can be used with it. - ATI grip - Tapco butt-stock - Rubber butt-plate extension  - Standard Saiga forend - Homemade comb - Standard Saiga rail mount - Weaver-style scope rail - Low-end Tasco 3-9x40 scope - 10 round plastic mag 
The rife is in great condition with a few minor blemishes at the front sight post area.  It has 30 rounds of jacketed rounds through it as well as 200 powder-coated lead rounds.  Feel free to ask me any questions.  I live in Hartford but I’ll meet you on a parking lot somewhere in the Waukesha area.  You must be 18, a Wisconsin resident, and not a felon.  I'm not desperate to sell; I just don't have time or space for more than a couple rifles.    
 $1000 or best offer -or- if you don't want the scope and rail, $950 obo  The story:  I'll keep it short as I already posted a write-up on castboolits.com about my foray into cast 7.62x39.  I purchased the Saiga several years ago but didn't do anything with it as I'm really only into bolt-guns.   Eventually as a hobby I decided to find out how much accuracy I could get out of the AK platform and set about making some changes as well as handloads for the 7.62x39.  Yes, I realize that there's at least 20 reasons why the AK and benchrest accuracy don't go together but I'm a reloader and wanted the challenge.  To the rifle I effected the following changes:
 
- I re-crowned the muzzle but kept the length.  Yes, I realize a 20" barrel won't be as accurate as a 16" but wanted to leave it intact, knowing that I would sell it.
- I removed (but later reinstalled) the front sight post.
- I added a 74 style brake to control barrel whip.
- I re-ground the gas tube so that it wouldn't impinge on the barrel so much when it heats up.
- I did put a much better trigger in but have returned the stock trigger to it.
 
Most importantly however were the handloads I developed.  AK throats are cavernous so I cast bullets that came to .315 after powder coating and seated them very far out.  The barrel on this rifle slugs to a tight .3115 which is great for any AK and typical for a Saiga.  My best handload is listed below if you're interested.  To not everyone's surprise however, I was never able to get a cast cartridge to chamber without the bolt stripping lead off of the top round in the magazine.  AKs have a particularly violent action and absolutely abuse cartridges going in and cases coming out.  With cast bullets, I was forced to hand chamber each one.  Anyway, the best I could do was 2 and 1 quarter inches at 100 yards, pretty good for an AK despite the 95% BS out there concerning accuracy.  Prior to all of this I fired a handful of jacketed bulk rounds through this rifle and scored 5 inches, typical for a high-end AK.  The rifle was cleaned (properly) twice; once after I fired the jacketed rounds, and once recently.  There's no leading or powder coat present and the gun functions flawlessly, as any AK should.  I still have the market stock if you want it.  Also, if you want the 7.62 dies, let me know and I'll sell them but would advise loading only jacketed or plated projectiles.  To sum it up, yes, this is a great rifle but no, you can't get any gains by firing cast loads through it.
 
My load:
 
- 150 grain (wheel weights) cast round nose, flat point dropped at .315 then red powder coat and swaged to .315
- Winchester brass expanded appropriately
- CCI primers
- 29.5 grains of BL-C2
- topped with 3 grains of cream-of-wheat
- COL of 2.190
- moderate crimp (to preserve .315)
